headline: Decibel Cannabis Reports 16% YoY Drop In Q1 Revenue,  CEO Expects Improved Q2 And 'Continued Path To Sustainable Growth And Profitability'
summary: Decibel Cannabis Company Inc. (TSXV: DB) (OTCQB: DBCCF), a maker of premium cannabis and extract manufactured products, announced on Wednesday its unaudited interim financial results for the three months ending March 31, 2024. The Calgary, Alberta-based company reported a year-over-year decrease of 16% in net revenue to $21 million. Benjamin Sze, the company's CEO said that "despite the drop in revenue, we remain one of Canada's top brands by market share." The company boasted a national market share of 6% in the first quarter, placing it as the 4th largest licensed producer in Canada by market share, the company said in a press release.

headline: As Federal Marijuana Reclassification Is Poised To Take Effect, These States Focus On Cannabis Reform
summary: In Massachusetts, the eliminated rule under which all marijuana deliveries are to be handled by two drivers is still enforced, according to CommonWealth Beacon's Bhaamati Borkhetaria.Last week, a measure that seeks to put an end to federal marijuana enforcement in legal states - the Strengthening the Tenth Amendment Through Entrusting States (STATES) 2.0 Act – got an endorsement from The Peace Officers Research Association of California (PORAC) and the Oregon Coalition of Police and Sheriffs (ORCOPs), reported Marijuana Moment.New Hampshire Senators gave the green light to a marijuana legalization measure on Thursday, following an initial floor vote earlier this month. The approval followed some major changes to the measure that now heads to the state's House of Representatives for concurrence on recent amendments, reported Marijuana Moment.Meanwhile, Senators in Louisiana approved the amended version of HB 165. The measure from state Rep. Delisha Boyd (D- New Orleans) seeks to decriminalize marijuana and the use of drug paraphernalia, reported KTVE.

The approval followed some major changes to the measure that now heads to the state's House of Representatives for concurrence on recent amendments, reported Marijuana Moment.Meanwhile, Senators in Louisiana approved the amended version of HB 165. (CSE: GRIN) (OTC: GRUSF) reported on Thursday its first-quarter 2024 results for the three months ended March 31, 2024.The Medford, Oregon-based company reported record quarterly revenue of $6.7 million, compared to $6 million in the three months ended April 30, 2023, representing a year-over-year increase of 11%."This was another exciting quarter with record revenue and aEBITDA despite the year-ago comparison period including April instead of January; April is seasonally a stronger month for the industry," Obie Strickler, CEO of Grown Rogue, said. "In addition, we achieved record indoor revenue in Michigan and Oregon during the quarter and are thrilled that an increasing number of customers in competitive markets are choosing our products which means we are continuing to bring them value."
text: Grown Rogue Reports Record Q1 Revenue, CEO Calls These Two States 'Primary Growth Drivers' Grown Rogue International Inc. (CSE: GRIN) (OTC: GRUSF) reported on Thursday its first-quarter 2024 results for the three months ended March 31, 2024.The Medford, Oregon-based company reported record quarterly revenue of $6.7 million, compared to $6 million in the three months ended April 30, 2023, representing a year-over-year increase of 11%."This was another exciting quarter with record revenue and aEBITDA despite the year-ago comparison period including April instead of January; April is seasonally a stronger month for the industry," Obie Strickler, CEO of Grown Rogue, said. "In addition, we achieved record indoor revenue in Michigan and Oregon during the quarter and are thrilled that an increasing number of customers in competitive markets are choosing our products which means we are continuing to bring them value."

headline: Restaurant Chain Cracker Barrel Posts Mixed Q3 Earnings Due To Lower Traffic: Details

The company revised its FY24 sales outlook to $3.47 billion - $3.51 billion.

headline: Bipartisan Push In Congress Seeks To Ease Access To Medical Marijuana For Veterans
summary: The latest bipartisan push in Congress to address cannabis reform comes as cannabis-related amendments to a large-scale spending bill covering Military Construction, Veterans Affairs, and Related Agencies (MilConVA) for the 2025 fiscal year that were filed recently.The measure from Reps. Brian Mast (R-FL), Earl Blumenauer (D-OR), Barbara Lee (D-CA) and Dave Joyce (R-OH) seek to enable veterans to take part in state medical marijuana programs and has its footholds in the Veterans Equal Access Act. The proposal would also abolish a directive that bars the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs doctors from issuing cannabis recommendations.
text: Bipartisan Push In Congress Seeks To Ease Access To Medical Marijuana For Veterans The latest bipartisan push in Congress to address cannabis reform comes as cannabis-related amendments to a large-scale spending bill covering Military Construction, Veterans Affairs, and Related Agencies (MilConVA) for the 2025 fiscal year that were filed recently.The measure from Reps. Brian Mast (R-FL), Earl Blumenauer (D-OR), Barbara Lee (D-CA) and Dave Joyce (R-OH) seek to enable veterans to take part in state medical marijuana programs and has its footholds in the Veterans Equal Access Act. The proposal would also abolish a directive that bars the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs doctors from issuing cannabis recommendations.

This facility will produce energy-efficient silicon carbide chips for electric vehicles. The aid includes a €2 billion direct grant. This move aims to strengthen Europe's semiconductor ecosystem and reduce reliance on imports, aligning with digital and green transition goals.

In the meantime, cannabis sales in North America seem to be thriving, if we factor in the number of new stores that are kicking off sales.
